properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heat event begins today. Daytime temperatures are expected to reach the low 30's with humidex values in the mid to high 30's today and Saturday. Overnight temperatures will remain near twenty, providing little relief from the heat. Temperatures will cool off slightly on Sunday. Hot and humid air can also bring deteriorating air quality and can result in the Air Quality Health Index approaching the high risk category. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Watch for the effects of heat illness: swelling, rash, cramps, fainting, heat exhaustion, heat stroke and the worsening of some health conditions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heat wave in sight. A warm and humid air mass will gradually settle over Southern Quebec. Maximum temperatures are forecast to reach or exceed 30 degrees on Saturday, Sunday and Monday. The weather will be particularly humid on Sunday and Monday when humidex values will hover between 38 and 42. The nights will also be uncomfortable. A cold front will bring some respite next Tuesday or Wednesday. Reschedule or plan your outdoor activities during the coolest time of the day. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. Description: At 9:03 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a very dangerous thunderstorm capable of producing destructive wind gusts, nickel to ping pong ball size hail and heavy rain. Doppler radar indicates potential for wind gusts of 140 km/h on a severe thunderstorm between Wilcox and Riceton. This thunderstorm is moving very quickly northwards at 70 km/h. ### This is a dangerous and potentially life-threatening situation. Widespread and extremely strong wind gusts can destroy buildings with tornado-like damage, flatten large stands of trees and blow vehicles off the road. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.
